Layer of overflow under layer of ice.

The first week of January we had lows of minus 35 to minus 52. The weather warmed the last week of January with one short rain and many days above freezing. The warmer weather and heavy snowfall led to the ice springing multiple open overflow holes. There was 6 cm of standing water on the ice under the snow when we shoveled the snow. It got measured as snow depth

Ice was milky white in location 1.  Ice was yellow in location 3.  Snowmachine trail ice thickness was 82 cm.  Under the bridge was 75+ (we needed an extension) Ranger Sam joined us.  We used his power auger to expedite the process.  We walked to the slough in snowshoes.  Saw lots of moose scat.

When we drilled down we hit some slushy mud but the ice was too close to the bottom for the metal (butterfly) device to turn and catch on the ice shelf--it simply stayed upright in the hole.  Ultimately\
Interal Notes: we used the measuring stick to get our measurement and our snow shoes to walk out into the middle of the lake. It's frozen to the bottom now.\n\n

Public Note with Ob: many other observations collected near Rosie Creek; MP data not yet available

Tested pH at all three Ice holes and it seemed high + 8 or above. Much evidence of snowshoe hare activity along the edge of the creek(willows). Several snow machine tracks had crossed the creek. Two ice holes had water trapped between layers. Temp was much warmer after a week of -40 and below weather.

Our transporters took the kids on snow machines to the middle of river for the measurements because others were seen traveling safely on it prior to our observation.  It was cloudy but temps were above zero and comfortable enough to be outside.  We had a fire and a picnic on the riverbank.
Significant cracks running down the slough and shelf ice drops along the banks
Looks like the lake had overflow and then froze. There was a layer of ice about 10cm and then a layer of water about 10cm and then solid ice below that.
Temp: 9F\
Deep fluffly snow. Water gushing up out of holes onto ice. Ice was dry on top before I made the holes. After making holes there was 3 cm of water on the ice.
Surprisingly we were able to easily shovel the snow all the way down to the ice again. The snow right above the ice was a little soggy though. All three holes gushed water\
Interal Notes: unlike last time when no water came out after drilling. We probably created an overflow situation! We used a drill with the auger this time and it made it super easy.

3" of water on top of the ice here (under the snow). We used our new\
Interal Notes: heavy-duty drill bit from Kovacs and had a much easier time trilling though our tricky lake ice. I'm curious to see how this new bit works next winter for us. We also got a nice new tape measuring system from them after the last setup broke at the beginning of the month.

column12: "Ice thickness at Calico bluff currently 51 inches. Mid- river main channel in area with no jumble ice. Little snowfall and high winds are keeping snow cover at a minimum all winter. River level is low. Bad freeze up at Eagle and 6 miles down stream. Extreme jumble in place. ice pack with little to no water beneath it to the bottom in many areas. I anticipate a late break up and high potential for ice jamming/flooding possible in the Eagle & Calico bluff area (14 miles downstream). Past two days are first spring thawing days. With below freeze temps at night. Bottom line as of now still winter like\
column14: no deterioration of snow pack measurable. No appreciable  loss of snow on the river yet."
